segments.text: Yeah.
Well, there was a lot of suffering that went on.
I guarantee you that in the military with Laos and Cambodia, at first you couldn't bomb.
Even Swede Larson, I told you about, he came back to Vietnam, had been a corps commander, and he told about the enemy across there in the border.
And he got called on the carpet and said, you got to call a press conference and tell them that you're mistaken.
Because it wasn't in the interest of the United States by someone to admit that there actually were North Vietnamese utilizing Laos and Cambodia, you know, coming on that.
So he called a news conference.
He said, well, I announced that the State Department knows more about what's going on in Laos and Cambodia than I do.
And I was wrong when I said there were North Vietnamese in Laos, particularly Laos.
Of course, later on, we know that we were bombing and doing good well.
But that's kind of the type of war.
I go on and I'm going to take the town and all sorts of things, you know.
Fortunately, the poor soldier down in Vietnam doesn't hear all these things.
like if you just got killed by somebody shooting across the border, you know, and say, oh, I didn't come across the border.
It was to the north.
Were you in Vietnam, or not Vietnam, in the Pentagon on January 31st, 1968, with a Tet Offensive?
Yeah.
Do you remember what the feeling in the Pentagon was about the Tet?
Because just four or five days earlier, General Westmoreland had
had made a major statement that we were winning and it was all downhill now, etc.
And then all of a sudden we had Tet.
Yeah, I think some were concerned about that, but I don't think it was as bad as the press reported, because actually Tet wasn't a victory for the North Vietnamese.
No, it was a victory for us.
It might have been embarrassing to Westmoreland to have sat down and have this large attack with the BC and the North enemy.
There was some real good street fighting in Saigon by, not the combat troops, but MPs and some of them.
They got into the streets of Saigon and were trying to get to the airfield, I'm sure, to get the Westmoreland Tent Corps.
So it didn't seem to have that much of an impact.
No.
What about the riots in the United States?
By 1967, 1968, there were a number of demonstrations against the war in Vietnam.
There were even some marches across the bridge in the Potomac and on the Pentagon and demonstrations outside.
What impact did that have on you and senior military officials?
I guess you'd call it disgust because you should have seen those people, who they were, or what they looked like.
Yeah, they tried, they tried to get in the, in the Pentagon, tried to get into the joint, yeah, and they were young.
It'd be long hair, smell stink for any of the girls.
They had intercourse right out there under the bushes.
We camped out, and the girls yelled.
See, we had soldiers who were blocking that.
They'd spit on them and throw things at them and call them all sorts of obscene names.
We kept the other entrance.
Fortunately, they had the front entrance there rather than being in the back.
So business went on as usual, and there didn't any of them get inside the Pentagon.
Basically, the officers were disgusted by the situation.
Is that the word?
Yeah.
Well, I know I was, and I think you all had to think, because it's different from some of the other demonstrations we've had, where you've had some clean, concerned citizen type of thing.
But they all looked and acted like
Some will admit now that the main reason I'm against the war is that I may have to go, or maybe I've already been called and I'm hiding out now.
So, you're discrediting what they expected to do in the Pentagon because we aren't the ones that decided it.
Of course, they were going to try to stop it, but I tried to stop it.
the work of government, you know, for a day or two days, like cluttering up the streets, throwing trash cans out, lying down in the street.
That was to keep people going to work.
But I say most of the disgust was the smoking of marijuana.
You could smell it just appalled all over that place.
And I said, actually, you could see these characters having intercourse under the bushes.
And then they camped out near the river down there.
And they went nude and had intercourse there.
You could see them from the street.
So it isn't exactly fine, idealistic young men and women that sincerely believe.
And I'm not saying they weren't sincere.
But I don't think that's an element of society that's going to impress me, particularly with their conduct.
Now, did the officers inside the Pentagon talk about these protests?
Oh, sure.
What was the general feeling?
Just exactly as I said.
And, of course, most of them would go a step further than I did in saying that we ought to get holes or something and push them away.
At least they'd get clean, see?
You couldn't do that, obviously, not in a Greek society like we have.
There's another thing I was wondering about, and that is the big question.
In your opinion, why did we lose in Vietnam?
That's difficult to answer.
As I've said before,
the military recommended against ever getting involved in Vietnam.
I know.
And they often quoted the wrong war at the wrong place at the wrong time.
And if anyone who would look around the map on here and say, now, where is the worst place you possibly could find to fight a war?
And you'd come to Southeast Asia, especially if you say,
The two countries are neutral, and you will not be able to conduct operations there, regardless of what happens.
Now look at this long, thin mass, see, with this unnatural line drawn up here that's going to be north and south.
And you go, who's the enemy?
Where are they?
Well, they're north of Vietnam.
No, they're not.
They're not down there, because that was our position.
There are no North Vietnamese South.
These are all patriotic, freedom-loving individuals who have their stomach full of this despotic leader, and they just want to eliminate that.
It's a civil war.
Now, how can you go in there and stabilize a civil war?
But the VC's been supported by the North Vietnamese, which in turn is supported by the USSR and also China.
Well,
How do you know that?
We don't think so.
Well, they have an agreement, like we have an agreement, to form support for a lot of countries, like Iran, for example.
That doesn't necessarily mean we're supporting them in war.
So as we talked about earlier, whether we were responsible or not, the leader they had was assassinated.
Well, some said he was Catholic, and the Catholics were.
were dominating the masses, see.
And if you just eliminated him, then you'd have peace.
Now, I have no at all information that we had anything to do with it.
Certainly not the assassination.
They're supposed to have been able to document that.
But I think we did have something to do with his elimination overthrow.
We didn't mean for him to be killed.
But I'm not even sure about that because I wasn't connected with it.
have no knowledge of.
But anyway, that was probably the first mistake.
Because it was downhill from then on.
Because he did at least have some following.
And if you could convince him to carry out the land reform that had been promised to him, and to be more tolerant from a religious standpoint, maybe it wouldn't have been so bad.
Maybe it would have happened anyway.

As far as you're concerned, who can, if the American public, we all seem to need a whipping boy, who would you blame as, or what part of society would you blame for the responsibility of losing that one?
Who has the main burden to bear?
Well, it's probably a combination of Congress and perhaps the President.
I guess the military in some way that I'm trying to think.
How, because our recommendation was never accepted.
But the same people have said, because they, well, you expect that from the military, you know, they'll shoot down everything in sight.
So there wasn't much attention ever given to the recommendation of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
At one read, you find that Air Force general acting as chairman was so abrupt, he saw an opportunity here.
He had the piece of paper, you know, he'd go to use his authority to get the bombing committed.
But it all started with Kennedy, with the special forces he was so on, that we would never have to have a large, continued troop.
They could go in there and help out, because they're going in
And their tribesmen there, just like in Iran, speak a different language.
They hate the central government.
You need people to go in there and train them.
They even have medical teams that can help them out.
They tend to stabilize the country, see.
And see if you can't get them to place their allegiance on the central government, see.
Communism never entered into it at that time.
These really were VCs that are unhappy.
They were unhappy ever since.
Going all the way back to the French.
All the way back, really, to World War II.
So do you see the war more as a nationalistic campaign than a communist one?
No, it developed into this, and we played the game.
By we, I mean this nation.
Later on, then, of course, when Paul D. Harkin, the one I mentioned, is retired in Dallas now.
He was a commanding general there after the Green Parade.
And he pointed out that with the present status quo there, we're not getting anywhere because what we wanted is a stable government with a unified country.
South now, we're not North, we're leaving that out.
South Vietnam, unified, land reform, stable government.
And that shouldn't be too hard to attain because then the VCs wasn't as strong as they later became.
But as we put in,
Then the North Vietnamese became more active, and the USSR supported them more so with equipment.
Now, we played their game.
We put in, they put in.
And it kept adding it up.
Pretty soon, we had hostilities.
And the South was secure, at least stable.
Later on, we put troops down in the South.
fought like hell down there see because then the BC came on down to Laos and Cambodia and there they were in there.
North Vietnamese even.
Now at one time we had the strength that we could have knocked North Vietnam out of the war.
We could have bombed the harbor with precision bombing which we later did.
It's true that we kind of scraped off the paint on a few Russian ships but
Nothing really came on it except, of course, they loudly protested.
We had the capability to completely destroy their war-making capability.
And we could have landed anywhere along that and actually occupied with Marines.
Occupied.
Not all, you wouldn't have to, but you could either go inland or you could make amphibious operations because they didn't have the power.
But that is the way we played the game, see.
a little bit more and a little bit more.
In other words, we almost told them, we won't use our power until you have a better chance of countering it.
Of course, that wasn't the thinking at all, but that's the way it turned out.
We didn't attack the North until they got rockets and improved their air defenses where they could shoot our planes out of the air, including B-52s.
We didn't use B-52s until they had a capability to shoot them out of the air.
They didn't have that capability at the beginning when we started having caveats down in the south.
Neither could the USR support them, because they had to bring things in from the USSR by ship.
China, really, as we found out now, as much as we know about them, they didn't have very much they could support them.
But they really didn't have a lot to give them.
But we didn't do that.
Now we're dragging on.
We have all these caveats.
And our nation turned against them.
They were tired.
And one thing that made them tired is looking at that dribble every single night on television.
Then, of course, they sought out their job to do that.
The most dastardly scenes and crimes that you could imagine.
So you put a large responsibility on the media?
Well, yes, but that's unfair.
Yes, I do.
Because I have heard
An individual.
I don't know his name.
It says that he was directed to submit copy based on a party line or position they had.
If he sent in copy and pictures that deviated from that, they would rewrite it and use the library of pictures to support that position.
That happened in Iran after most of that.
I was on a ship going to London, airplane, going to London to a meeting.
Syngnam had that Persian Gulf area responsibility then.
After that, there was really a planning meeting for Iran.
And this plane was full of correspondents that had been in there covering the Iranians.
And I guess it was Life magazine.
Either Life or Time, I've already forgotten.
had just come out with a cover story and all those things.
And these others were razzing this guy about his copy.
They said, you know that didn't happen like that.
Where'd you get all that stuff?
He says, well, that's not what I submitted.
That was rewritten.
And he said, you see that picture there?
I didn't take that picture of the photographer.
That's a picture that was taken in North Africa.
If you look closely, you can see that that's not an Iranian standing there.
That's an Arab.
And that's a different tank.
And do you have proof that the media was doing things like this in Vietnam?
Or are these just things that you heard?
Well, I don't personally have proof, but there are others that have proof of that because they talked to somebody that day.
Most of it was hack truth, not fabrication.
You can take a picture and write any kind of story you want to.
But it wasn't favorable, I'll put it that way.
Then later on, I know this to be a fact.
In many of the newsrooms and places, they had LBJ's pictures and they used it as a dart.
They wouldn't anymore write anything favorable about LBJ because they hated him.
One reason they hated him, you know why?
He insisted on going out here to the ranch and living, see.
And the press, we didn't even have the nice hotels we have here now.
They had to stay at the Stephen F. Austin and a bunch of these ratty-looking hotels and had to commute back and forth.
And it was very uncomfortable.
And they blamed him for making life miserable for them.
And they wouldn't anymore give him good coffee.
Now, him and the person wouldn't make any difference, but he attacked the war and everything to get at him or him because of the war.
So the whole thing just got this country
So sick, including even the military, going on and on and on like that.
You see how Congress changed.
They voted two votes against the Gulf of Tonkin residents, the guy from Alaska and old Morris, I guess.
I guess he's from Dakota, isn't he?
They were the two who voted against him, Fulbright and Leslie.
And they practically gave the president anything he wanted to.
It was an undeclared, declared war.
And so he started up.
But in summary, it looks like the whole thing, in your opinion, is a mess.
Terrible.
Well, let's go ahead.
Just like the desert operation.
That's terrible.
Terrible.
Made the military look like acid.
Wore out our equipment.
All of these caves.
Billions of dollars.
Just think how much we made.
One of the reasons for inflation is because
What do we do?
We just printed more money, see?
Didn't raise taxes.
We didn't call up the reserves, because they didn't want to, supposed to upset the reason, of course.
Good reason we didn't declare war, because that had a lot of trade implications worldwide.
Had all these games, but for what?
Sounds like you're demoralized.
We expanded, instead of calling up the reserves,
We expanded Austin Candidate School in the draft.

So what we brought in, 18 and 19-year-old, 20 years old, we actually, short of noncommissioned Austin, so we identified these young men in basic training that indicated at that short time an aptitude for leadership.
And of course, you go by, interview some, you know, what you asked for, you're a leader, you know, what did you do?
He probably was captain of this football team, leading the debate
something.
Anyway, he indicated something.
So right then, we put a thing around his arm and he becomes what amounts to as a corporal.
He's a squad leader.
He's a contemporary of these guys.
They came in together.
So we keep on and hopefully he is having to learn leadership at the same time basic training.
And we go on where he becomes a leader.
He's identified as a potential non-commissioned officer.
Then he's just in his training unit, you know.
So with that, we gave him some additional training.
Oftentimes, he gets to Vietnam before these other kids that he came in to serve.
That's the young man who's a non-comm for this other private, although I'm not the same age.
He's expecting, you know.
that he's expecting he does.
He's fighting a war.
This guy here responds with his squad.
And then he finally, if he survives, he gets to be a platoon sergeant.
OCS the same way.
They're young.
They end up by having an OCS graduate just out of school with his non-comm that's just out of basic training, advanced individual training, not just basic training.
Then above him, you've got a captain.
Who is this captain?
He graduated mostly about two or three months ago, maybe longer now that he's a captain.
But oftentimes the characters were so high, I won't exaggerate, make him a company commander as a first lieutenant.
And then that applied in just a short time.
Now our policy of rotating officers, we tried to leave them in there not much over a year.
This pipeline keeps coming in from the state.
Now we're rotating the officers, so when they get a year's experience, they're gone, and somebody new comes in.
So you've got inexperience leading to inexperience, and it just keeps going like that.
It's just terrible.
That's the reason I say, if you sat down with what I know now, the school and the experience, and tried to figure out where in the world would you
select not to fight a war, after having select this gosh awful place, how can I structure my personnel management procedure and principle to add to that terrible place?
Well, I would come up with what I just described.
Now, how would you handicap these people in this terrible place, restrict the bombing
and air support to just in front of them.
But this is a guerrilla-type war.
You can't see the VC.
Well, we'll use the foliage.
We'll just clear out all of the underbrush, you know.
All of that time and energy, and now it turns out it's probably a terrible thing.
They say, well, that's great that we got that.
Well, what about North Vietnam?
Well, don't touch them, because it's our policy that they're not in South Vietnam.
It's our policy.
It's not in Cambodia.
It's our policy.
It's not in Laos.
But we see them there.
You don't understand.
Now, are you giving these kids really a fair shake?
Now, I add to this.
These are the kids that are not going to college.
Many of them are black, more than their proportion in our population.
And is this fair?
And that's the reason why I don't have any patience with all these who missed all of this, because they should suffer like these guys.
So you feel that our soldiers in the field were treated unfairly from a number of viewpoints.
They just weren't given the support.
That's right.
Now you've got them in there.
Now they're rotating.
They see all of them die.
It looks like that they may...
I had the same feeling in Italy.
I don't know how many people we lost here going...
Three miles, look how many miles I got to go ahead of all these mountains.
Nobody could possibly survive that thing.
Here they are.
They're hopeful that they can survive for their year where they can go back.
It wasn't like that.
Even in Korea, we had success.
Vietnam, you know, it's searching.
Search and destroy.
Search and destroy, and you go out and you come back.
Muddy, raining.
But I think if we go in and support and say, okay, we didn't declare the war in Korea.
This is not a war, but we're going to fight it like a war.
And if we get somebody exposed to death, then we owe it to him.
We're going to give him full support.
And we're here.
The best way we can stabilize a country is clear it out.
and not fool around with a pocket of B.C.
here and there and send out.
We finally got so scattered that we had to use most of our troops to secure our bases.
There's no way to fight a war.
What you have to do is clear it out the way that you don't have to do it.
Let's go on to your last assignment at Fort Monroe, Virginia.
Were you happy to leave the Pentagon after three years of pressure?
Well, yeah.

Anybody, see, because I lived in, as we talked about, in Fairfax, Virginia, and had to commute heavy traffic, which took quite a considerable time, because what I did, usually, go to work real early, and then come back after the rush.
Most of the people, most of the rush was on the bureaucratic time table.
But I was ready to move on to something else because that's long enough.
And I was delighted to go to Fort Monroe because Fort Monroe is a beautiful old post, one of the oldest posts in the United States.
In fact, when they settled Jamestown, they dropped off a contingent there on the, not Fort Monroe then, but on this point.
They had to guide the ships up the channel toward Jamestown.
And at Fort Monroe, you were assistant deputy chief of staff for individual training.
Yeah, we were responsible.
What does that mean?
We were responsible for all the training centers in the United States.
And all of the schools in the United States.
That's a tremendous responsibility.
And we had the responsibility for each week bringing in draftees.
we'd have to decide which training center they would be sent.
And sometimes we'd have to reschedule them because we had a...
In the United States, the draft, well, as you'd expect, it was not the same.
We'd get a heavy load for one part of the country and a weak load in another.
And we had to decide, based on capacity, which of those may be shipped.
That's the first problem.
And then the second problem, after they've been through basic training, where we send them for advanced individual training.
In the Vietnam War, we were using all our facilities.
I'm dumb.
No, that's why I was quite a junk.
And then after they graduate, of course, the Pentagon assigned them to the unit.
But we were responsible for providing transportation from the training center to whatever destination that they're going.
Now, we were responsible on the staff level, of course, the people like down in the base camp were the ones who actually rounded up the transportation.
Then the school, we were responsible for the administration of the school, the curriculum, standards were maintained.
And all the schools have quite a few.
How many service schools were there in the Army at that time?
Do you have any?
I got a black one.
So there's about 20 different Army service schools here.
Okay, so the big problem was the budget.
You had to fight for how much money was going to be budgeted for each school.
Everywhere, right.
And there are loads.
Of course, during the Vietnam War, all of them had a tremendous load, but I didn't necessarily have the sufficient funds to support it.
And I enjoyed that because I did a lot of traveling there.
I would imagine going from school to school, checking out the training units.
Especially the training centers, because the training centers,
being full and having these young men and having problems with heat exhaustion and drill sergeants.
And we were responsible that the standard was maintained at all training centers and not have one.
And you could tell.
You get the end product, and sometimes they could tell which training center they were from.
And we tried to correct that, at least to get them all
up to the standard of our best one.
And that had a lot to do, of course, with the commanding general, the way that he conducted the training, and how closely he supervised the training.
Did training change because of Vietnam?
Was there a lot more influence on guerrilla warfare?
There was.
Each training center, we even built villages like that in Vietnam.
of all the different types of weapons that they used, techniques they used, so that when he got there, he had some kind of idea of what to expect rather than having to learn the first week or two.
And during this period, of course, there was a tremendous increase in the number of blacks and the number of women.
into the armed forces.
And there must have been an increase of those into the service schools.
Not women.
Not women.
Well, we increased the WACs, but is that what you mean?
Yeah.
But not integrated into the unit.
They served as WACs, as medical specialists, as typeists, communication, that sort of thing.
But nothing like we have now.
Right.
And did you have any, during this time, of course, this is the rise of black power, and there were a number of black riots in the United States from 65 to 68 or so.
Did this have any impact on your training centers?
Did you have any racial incidents?
Oh, isolated ones, because you had those before there, but there was no evidence of any distrust or
between the races are really antagonistic.
In fact, they got real close in Vietnam, because all these deaf mixed partners of a lot of strange people, you know.
Boy, sure.
Got to be close buddies.
Also, during this time, there was a switch in administrations from the Johnson Democratic administration to the Nixon Republicans.
And I was wondering if that change had any impact
on the way that you ran any of these schools?
Because he did have a different approach toward Vietnam, somewhat different, that is, escalation in the bombing and the invasion into Cambodia, Mr. Nixon.
So that basically knows the facts.
Not really.
Now, you take our aviation school.
And I even had difficulty getting some of our military planners to understand this.
That's a school where you have a long lead time.
And you can't cut that old spigot off like you can a lot of places.
You already have these in the pipeline.
So as it started winding down the war, of course, schools like the aviation school had to reduce the load.
And we closed.
which was one big problem.
Mineral wells, you know, that was our helicopter school, our base school.
Real fine with the weather.
People around there were great because they would permit you to use their ranch land with no rental at all.
Go in and out and use it.
So we closed that down.
Did get permission.
You're able to do things in Texas a little bit more.
Of course, that wasn't such a
source of income for the community.

Of course, it was immediate mineral wells, but as you find, like Fort Dix up in New Jersey, we've been trying to close Fort Dix for years, and we probably never will, because most of our facilities are down in the south, and they say, here, you're closing out all of the facilities in the northeast part of the United States, and
putting them down in Georgia, Carolina, Texas, Louisiana.
What about the Air Cavalry?
This is, of course, new in the Army.
Yeah.
And did that have any impact on your training?
Yeah.
They, too, that aviation necessary to
and additional courses down at our aviation school, which is down in Alabama.
But that's not too difficult.
Of course, you need funds each time in your budget.
But it's not too difficult to expand courses if you have an active school and those trained
instructor that experienced it.
But we ended up, of course, at the end of the Vietnam War, with more aviators than we needed, obviously.
And that becomes a morale problem because we phased out some of the warrant officers who were aviated to make room for commissioned officers.
And I was wondering why they decided to take high school graduates and then train them
to fly helicopters and make them warrant officers in the first place instead of using commissioned officers.
Why was that?
The only thing I know is that when I was involved with this thing, the need for aviators was so great, and you could train a warrant officer, CS Limited,
responsibility.
You could actually say all you're going to do is fly a plane and at least have military knowledge and other things so that you can adjust the environment.
But an officer is supposed to have a broader knowledge.
It takes more time.
Now, a good question, another good question would be, why don't you have sergeants flying helicopters?
Because some countries have sergeants flying helicopters.
Why do you have to be a warrant officer?
I can't answer that, except no one seems to be receptive to that idea at all.
One thing goes, a warrant officer gets more pay.
You get a senior warrant officer, he makes more than a captain.
So for the pay scale, that's probably...
But did you take a lot of people who were in sergeant position at the time and offer them a warrant officer position if they went to a helicopter?
Yeah, and some did that.
Of course, you had to have some additional schooling because a warrant officer has to know more than just fly the plane.
Sure.
But yeah, they did that.
We had a warrant officer program.
You could either...
planned to become a warrant officer through the system, or for those sergeants who were qualified, mentally and physically, could apply for it and then become a warrant officer.
Why did you decide to retire?
Well, I didn't have any other choice.
I didn't get promoted.
And one of the reasons I didn't is because of a fact I had on my record showed physical limitations.
And so I retired at 30% disability.
I didn't want to retire.
Gosh, I'd still be there at age 65 if it weren't for being retired.
But I'm very happy in retirement.
I've done all of the things that I wanted to do.
But you didn't have firm plans.
I think we were talking about this earlier, but you didn't have firm plans like you wanted to go to work for a corporation or something like that.
I was just looking for something that I could contribute something to.
I talked to Nat Allen about Allen Academy.
I was willing to go there, work there for him for free if I could just do something.
But Nat told me that, of course, he doesn't have anything to do with it.
He may still work there.
I don't know who owns Allen Academy now.
But he said, I know there will be problems
I think he really thought that I meant to pay me something.
If they were having a financial problem, they'd still be happy.
But I had already told you about going out to A&M.
Once again, then I was willing to do anything.
I might contribute something.
And I think that young man thought guys like me were a threat to them.
Did their promotions a job?
He hasn't bought it.
I'm sure you've had your career.
What do you mean, coming out here?
So I wasn't disappointed, except I would like to build around that.
Now, you had a special review when you did retire from Port Monroe, Virginia.
Can you tell me a little about that?
It's just about over.
They asked me for songs there.
What's Our Favorite, Stevie Gaines, those things.
Then I had the Warrant and Standing Service Medal.
It was more or less a routine type of a General Lawson title.
Were you sad to leave the service?
Oh, yeah.
Did you feel bitter toward the service?
Oh, no.
I love the service.
It's been very good to me.
I don't see how anybody could be better.
Well, I can see why.
Maybe someone like a Vietnam veteran would, because he suffered so much, and he'd get kicked out.
Nobody cared.
Mainly his community, that's what's sad.
See, we all came back in World War II, and the lowliest guy, he may not have even been in combat, but he was a hero, because he went and served his nation and made the sacrifice.
Even in Korea when they came back, it was a little bit better because, see, we did call some reserves for Korea, the National Guard.
